# PLAN-003 — Phase 1 verdict integrity and metrics semantics

## 1. Decision & non-goals

Phase 1 will make test execution and binary review verdicts mechanically trustworthy before any candidate can advance to PR creation. The installed parent dispatcher—not the candidate’s dispatcher—will select required tests from the actual base-to-candidate diff. Required trust-suite tests will execute from content bound to the installed parent commit while targeting the candidate worktree; candidate-modified test copies may run additionally but can never satisfy the parent-required attestation. The dispatcher will stop at the test gate unless every required trusted test executed at least one assertion and passed.

Review verdict schema v4 will bind one ordered verdict entry to every acceptance criterion and represent scope, regression, and security findings with structured severities that mechanically block a PASS. The existing shared gate-venv and sanitized-reviewer-log design is retained.

Metrics work will first extract reporting from the trust-critical dispatcher through a behavior-preserving high-assurance change. A following ordinary-risk reporting change will remove unsupported direct-merge attribution and define straight-through rate per completed spec rather than per attempt. The ordinary-risk metrics dispatch will have no write scope over `scripts/dispatch.py`. Corrected metrics semantics remain the prerequisite for Phase 2’s measurement layer.

Assertion-event migration across the existing shell suite will be a separate high-assurance predecessor. This keeps the homogeneous mechanical migration independently reviewable before the dispatcher, runner, isolation, policy, and reviewer-evidence changes are reviewed.

Non-goals:

- Do not change the worker model, reasoning depth, priority service tier, reviewer seat, branch topology, or human merge authority.
- Do not permit the candidate checkout to run its own gate implementation or supply the authoritative copy of a required trust-suite test. Candidate code may be the subject of tests, but the dispatcher, required-test content, test policy, attestation aggregator, and gate-transition logic must come from the installed parent version recorded in the attempt manifest.
- Do not repair unrelated isolation, stale-base, manual-merge, resource-ceiling, approval-binding, or evidence-retention findings.
- Do not infer whether an unmatched commit was written or merged by a human, operator, bot, or external automation.
- Do not turn Phase 1 metrics into a broader analytics or measurement layer. Phase 2 remains gated on the narrowly corrected metrics semantics.
- Do not make reviewer judgment authoritative for whether tests executed, whether criteria are complete, whether required test content was trusted, or whether a finding blocks.
- Do not parse human-readable `SKIP`, `PASS`, or assertion text from `test.log` as authorization input.
- Do not expose the operator’s home or `.venv`, install packages from the candidate checkout, enable network access in the isolated test unit, or install dependencies as `codex-worker`.
- Do not alter, replace, or append to `.orchestrator/attempts/SPEC-015/1/*`. Historical evidence is immutable.
- Do not retroactively convert legacy verdicts to v4. Legacy artifacts remain displayable but cannot authorize a new or resumed gate decision.
- Do not redesign the spec schema beyond any mechanical compatibility change strictly required to name test IDs. Required-test selection remains a parent-owned policy derived from changed paths.
- Do not authorize an incompatible test-semantics change merely because the candidate supplies a replacement test. Such a change must use the compatibility sequence or separately authorized bootstrap procedure defined in §4.4.

## 2. Current-state evidence

### 2.1 Observed facts

1. The current test gate writes `test.log` and uses the child process return code as its success signal; it does not validate which tests or assertions executed (`scripts/dispatch.py:935-951`).

2. The repository test wrapper treats any child exit code of zero as `PASS`; it has no separate successful-skip state (`scripts/test:22`). That is why a test can print `SKIP`, exit zero, and immediately be reported as passing.

3. The recorded SPEC-015 run proves this is not hypothetical:

   - `dispatch_gate4.sh` skipped because PyYAML/jsonschema were absent (`.orchestrator/attempts/SPEC-015/1/test.log:7`).
   - `dispatch_parallel.sh` skipped for the same reason (`.orchestrator/attempts/SPEC-015/1/test.log:10`).
   - `worker_isolation.sh` skipped because its on-box prerequisites were absent (`.orchestrator/attempts/SPEC-015/1/test.log:30`).
   - These tests correspond to live trust-boundary test surfaces in `tests/dispatch_gate4.sh`, `tests/dispatch_parallel.sh`, and `tests/worker_isolation.sh`; their current prerequisite branches return successful skip rather than a gate failure.

4. The reviewer received only the statement that `./scripts/test` exited zero (`scripts/dispatch.py:1186-1188`; `.orchestrator/attempts/SPEC-015/1/raw/review-request.txt:54-57`). Reviewer filesystem tools were denied, so it could not read the omitted test log (`scripts/dispatch.py:1191-1200`).

5. Despite those skips, the stored verdict marked all seven criteria `MET` and claimed dynamic test proof that did not exist (`.orchestrator/attempts/SPEC-015/1/review.json:5,10,15,20,25,30,35`). This is the required historical regression case.

6. The current verdict schema requires only one `criteria[]` item. “One entry per acceptance criterion” is descriptive text rather than an enforced spec-dependent constraint (`scripts/verdict.schema.json:8-11`).

7. `evaluate_binary_review()` currently examines only the criterion entries the reviewer supplied and accepts a PASS when all supplied entries are `MET`; it does not establish that the list is complete or bound to the spec (`scripts/dispatch.py:1106-1116`).

8. Review validation currently binds `spec_digest`, `base_sha`, and `worker_commit`, which proves artifact identity but not criterion completeness or evidentiary truth (`scripts/dispatch.py:1119-1134`).

9. Scope, regression, and security findings are presently required as nonempty prose but do not mechanically affect a PASS. A verdict can therefore describe a critical finding and still be accepted by `evaluate_binary_review()` (`scripts/dispatch.py:1106-1116`).

10. The worker-controlled diff is read and inserted into the reviewer prompt (`scripts/dispatch.py:1141,1188`). This is an untrusted prompt channel even though no prompt injection was identified in SPEC-015.

11. The CI contract is the single non-matrix job named `ci` in `.github/workflows/ci.yml`. It runs the repository entry point but does not itself cure a successful prerequisite skip; the new attestation semantics must therefore be exercised in CI rather than relying on the workflow’s aggregate exit status.

12. The reporting code currently gives the complement of orchestrator-attributed merges a direct-merge actor attribution in `scripts/delegation_report.py` even though the available evidence establishes only that those commits were not matched to an orchestrator record. The same reporting surface’s `dispatch metrics` calculation treats attempts as the rate population, allowing retries to change both numerator and denominator instead of measuring completed specs. These are semantic reporting defects, not gate-state defects.

13. `scripts/dispatch.py` is in the dispatcher trust closure. A path-based scope gate cannot mechanically constrain an ordinary-risk worker to only its metrics functions. Therefore the reporting logic must be extracted through a separately authorized high-assurance change before ordinary-risk metrics semantics can be changed safely.

### 2.2 Assumptions

1. `scripts/requirements.txt` remains the trusted source of pinned Python dependencies. This plan does not alter dependency versions.

2. The operator can provision `/srv/codexwork/venvs/gate/<requirements-sha256>` through the existing privileged setup procedure before activating the repaired test gate.

3. The installed parent checkout and its executable path can be recorded in each attempt manifest. If they cannot be resolved to a trusted commit, dispatch fails closed.

4. Existing shell tests can be migrated mechanically to a shared assertion helper without changing what they test. This assumption must be demonstrated through the mutation drill in R1 and §8.4; it is not accepted merely because the migrated suite remains green.

5. A machine can prove that trusted test content ran and emitted assertion results; it cannot prove that every assertion is semantically sufficient. Parent-owned test selection and content, migration-fidelity mutation drills, scope review, bound review, and human authorization remain necessary.

6. Historical raw logs may be unavailable in a clean CI checkout because raw attempt evidence is gitignored. Therefore validation uses both an on-box read-only replay of the real SPEC-015 evidence and a tracked synthetic fixture containing the same missing-attestation/skip pattern. The fixture is regression input, not replacement historical evidence.

7. Required trust tests can be adapted during the migration predecessor to distinguish their trusted source root from the candidate target root. A test that cannot make that distinction is not eligible to authorize a candidate until its adapter is corrected and installed as parent content.

8. A candidate test change that intentionally contradicts an installed parent test cannot be authorized by substituting the candidate copy. The normal route is the two-stage compatibility sequence in §4.4. An exceptional incompatible bootstrap requires authority outside this plan.

9. Any drift in the cited symbols before authorization requires refreshing citations and re-running challenge. It does not reopen the decisions in this plan.

## 3. Requirements & acceptance criteria

### R1. Machine-enforced, parent-content-bound required-test attestation

The parent test gate must possess an exact, parent-selected set of required test IDs. The authoritative content for every required trust-suite ID must come from the installed parent commit recorded in the attempt manifest, not from the candidate worktree. Each trusted test must target the candidate checkout through the parent-owned target-root interface.

Each required ID must be launched exactly once from its trusted source, exit zero, emit at least one valid passing assertion event, emit no failing assertion event, and finish with status `PASS`. A required `SKIP`, absent trusted test, duplicate result, zero-assertion result, malformed event, stale nonce, nonzero exit, missing source binding, source-blob mismatch, target-root mismatch, or missing aggregate attestation must produce `failed_test` before reviewer invocation. Aggregate command exit zero is never sufficient.

Candidate-modified copies of required tests must be detected from the base-to-candidate diff and run as supplemental tests. They may add evidence and may fail the gate, but their assertions never count toward the parent-required set and cannot replace or suppress a trusted result.

Acceptance criteria:

1. A fixture in which one required trusted test prints `SKIP` and exits zero ends as `failed_test`; review and PR-opening spies have zero calls.
2. A required trusted test that exits zero without emitting an assertion event ends as `failed_test` with reason `zero_assertions`.
3. Missing, duplicated, unknown, escaping, symlinked, non-regular, or parent-commit-mismatched required test IDs fail closed.
4. A result with a stale run nonce, wrong base/head binding, wrong parent source commit, wrong trusted blob hash, wrong target root, duplicate sequence, unknown status, or overall `PASS` inconsistent with a child result fails closed.
5. A candidate touching `scripts/dispatch.py` and declaring `test_command: true` still runs the parent-selected, parent-content-bound trust suite against the candidate tree; the declared command cannot satisfy or replace required IDs.
6. Every required ID appears exactly once in the persisted trusted attestation with its parent commit, trusted blob hash, candidate target commit, positive assertion count, zero child exit, and `PASS` before review can begin.
7. The actual `.orchestrator/attempts/SPEC-015/1/test.log`, supplied without a valid structured attestation, replays to a blocking `legacy_missing_attestation` result without modifying any SPEC-015 file.
8. Replacing a candidate copy of a required test with a stub that reads the injected environment, emits well-formed passing events, and exits zero does not satisfy the required result. The trusted parent copy still runs, and the persisted aggregate separates `trusted_required_results` from `candidate_supplemental_results`.
9. Deleting or renaming the candidate copy of a required test does not remove the trusted execution. The deletion or rename is recorded as a changed-test condition and processed under §4.4.
10. For every assertion-helper form introduced by the migration, and for at least one migrated test representing each distinct shell assertion idiom, an induced failure of the guarded condition must emit `ok: false` and exit nonzero. No tested helper form may emit `ok: true` before its condition is evaluated.
11. A candidate-added required-test proposal cannot become authoritative during its own attempt. It is supplemental until merged, installed, and rerun from the newly installed parent during the activation drill.

### R2. Verdict schema v4 criterion count and identity binding

Verdict schema v4 must require `schema_version: 4` and structured `criteria[]` entries. Dispatcher-side validation must require the criteria list to have exactly the same length and order as the bound spec’s `acceptance_criteria`. Every entry must carry its one-based `criterion_index`, and its criterion text must match the corresponding spec criterion exactly or under the normalization defined in §4.6. Missing, extra, reordered, duplicated, or mismatched criteria reject the verdict before binary evaluation.

Acceptance criteria:

1. For an N-criterion spec, only a verdict with exactly N criteria entries can pass.
2. Omitting one entry, adding one entry, duplicating an index, reordering entries, using a zero- or out-of-range index, or substituting invented criterion text rejects the verdict fail-closed.
3. Exact text and the explicitly defined whitespace/Unicode-normalized equivalent pass binding; case, punctuation, Markdown, or wording changes do not.
4. A schema-valid PASS with every supplied criterion `MET` still fails if criterion count or binding is wrong.
5. Legacy v1-v3 artifacts remain readable for display but are never accepted for a new or resumed review decision.

### R3. Structured blocking findings

Schema v4 must replace prose-only scope, regression, and security finding fields with arrays of structured finding objects. Each finding requires `severity`, `summary`, and `evidence`; allowed severities are exactly `advisory` and `blocker`. An empty array means no finding. `evaluate_binary_review()` must return failure if any of the three arrays contains `severity: blocker`. Missing arrays, non-arrays, malformed entries, absent or unknown severity, or evaluation exceptions are treated as blockers even if upstream schema validation was accidentally bypassed.

Acceptance criteria:

1. A verdict with all criteria `MET` and one blocker in any of `scope_findings`, `regression_findings`, or `security_findings` is rejected.
2. An all-`MET` PASS with empty finding arrays or advisory-only findings may pass if every other binding succeeds.
3. `critical`, `high`, empty, null, misspelled, numeric, or otherwise unknown severity values are rejected; no substring search or severity inference is used.
4. Direct unit tests of `evaluate_binary_review()` prove that malformed findings fail closed even when called without prior schema validation.
5. The reviewer prompt and schema examples use the same structured vocabulary; no production branch continues accepting prose-only finding strings.

### R4. Shared isolated gate environment

Tests requiring PyYAML/jsonschema must run using a content-addressed virtual environment derived from the trusted parent checkout’s `scripts/requirements.txt`. It must be readable and executable but not writable by `codex-worker`. Missing, stale, mismatched, writable, or unusable environments block the test gate without falling back to operator-home, system packages, network installation, or unisolated execution.

Acceptance criteria:

1. The exact isolated on-box test unit imports `yaml` and `jsonschema` through `/srv/codexwork/venvs/gate/<digest>` and executes the required dispatcher assertions.
2. As `codex-worker`, imports succeed but create, replace, remove, rename, and chmod operations inside the shared venv fail.
3. A missing or mismatched digest marker blocks before any required test and before review.
4. A candidate change to `scripts/requirements.txt` blocks until the operator provisions the matching trusted-parent digest; candidate-authored requirements are never installed during the gate.
5. No production or test path references `/home/val/.venv`, performs `pip install` as `codex-worker`, enables network access, or falls back to an unisolated command.

### R5. Reviewer receives bounded, sanitized test evidence

After R1 succeeds, the reviewer request must include the trusted structured attestation plus a bounded, sanitized tail of `test.log`. The log remains explicitly untrusted data. Missing, symlinked, changing, oversized-beyond-policy, or unreadable evidence blocks review rather than silently degrading to an exit-code summary.

Acceptance criteria:

1. The reviewer request identifies every required test, its trusted source commit and blob hash, candidate target commit, assertion count and PASS status, the full-log hash, byte counts, line counts, and truncation status.
2. A recognizable final test-log line is present as JSON-escaped evidence; the request contains more than “exited 0.”
3. ANSI controls, NUL/C0/C1 controls, invalid UTF-8, delimiter text, Markdown fences, and instruction-like text cannot alter fixed reviewer instructions or create a closing delimiter.
4. Only the final 16 KiB and final 80 logical lines are supplied; the complete raw log remains unchanged.
5. Test-log bytes never appear in process arguments or shell interpolation.
6. Deleting, replacing, symlinking, or racing the log between validation and prompt construction blocks review.

### R6. Correct metrics semantics

The reporting-only metrics implementation in `scripts/metrics_report.py` must rename every actor-attributing direct-merge label to `not_attributed_to_orchestrator`, with explanatory text that actor identity is unknown. The metrics command must calculate straight-through rate per eligible completed spec:

- Denominator: distinct specs with a terminal dispatch result in the selected corpus/window.
- Numerator: denominator specs whose first and only attempt reached the normal orchestrator `merged` terminal state after all gates, with no retry, rebase replacement, manual override, or later attempt.
- Each spec contributes at most once.
- In-progress or structurally incomplete specs are excluded and separately counted.
- A zero denominator produces JSON `null` and display `N/A`, not `0%` or `100%`.

Acceptance criteria:

1. No output, JSON key, heading, or help text attributes an unmatched merge to a human or operator.
2. The replacement label is `not_attributed_to_orchestrator` and explains only the mechanically supported fact.
3. A committed fixture containing one first-attempt merge, one retry-then-merge, one terminal first-attempt failure, one in-progress spec, and one malformed/incomplete record produces numerator `1`, denominator `3`, rate `1/3`, excluded-in-progress `1`, and malformed/incomplete `1`.
4. Adding attempts to the retrying spec does not change the denominator or numerator.
5. Empty eligible input returns `null`/`N/A` without division errors.
6. Existing non-rate counts remain unchanged unless their labels asserted unsupported actor attribution.
7. Phase 2 measurement work cannot dispatch until the ordinary-risk metrics semantics dispatch is merged and its fixture passes on `integration`.
8. The ordinary-risk metrics semantics dispatch has no allowed path in the dispatcher trust closure and cannot modify `scripts/dispatch.py`, `scripts/dispatch`, gate transitions, attempt serialization, or authorization logic.
9. The preceding high-assurance extraction preserves the existing metrics behavior byte-for-byte or field-for-field, except for unavoidable module-origin metadata explicitly enumerated in its spec.
10. Non-metrics dispatcher commands neither import nor depend on `scripts/metrics_report.py`; failure to import the reporting module cannot alter a gate command’s behavior.

### R7. Bootstrap and evidence invariants

Every spec in this plan must be gated by the installed parent dispatcher recorded before candidate work begins. The candidate’s `scripts/dispatch.py`, test aggregator, policy, schema validator, evaluator, or required-test copy must never be selected as its own gate implementation or authoritative trust test. Attempts and raw evidence remain append-only/immutable.

Acceptance criteria:

1. The attempt manifest records the installed parent executable realpath and parent commit.
2. A candidate dispatcher replaced with a marker-writing stub is not invoked by the gate; the marker remains absent.
3. Gate commands use absolute parent-controlled executable, policy, runner, helper, and trusted-test paths while targeting the candidate worktree as data.
4. SPEC-015 evidence hashes and bytes are unchanged after replay.
5. New failed-test and failed-review artifacts are retained; no rollback or compatibility path rewrites them as passes.
6. Every high-assurance dispatch has the required operator approval artifact bound to its digest and attempt. An approval for one dispatch, attempt, or test-content digest cannot authorize another.
7. Activation of a newly merged parent is conditional on rerunning its newly authoritative tests from that installed parent against the exact merged commit.

## 4. Design / approach

### 4.1 Dispatch decomposition and dependency order

| Order | Dispatch | Lane | Dependency | Purpose |
|---:|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | Metrics extraction | high-assurance | None | Move metrics implementation behind a standalone reporting module while preserving behavior; remove ordinary metrics work from the dispatcher trust closure. |
| 2 | Metrics semantics | ordinary | Dispatch 1 merged and installed | Correct attribution naming and straight-through-rate semantics without allowing writes to `scripts/dispatch.py`; unblock Phase 2. |
| 3 | Assertion-event migration | high-assurance | Dispatch 2 merged | Homogeneously migrate the shell suite to assertion events, explicit exit-77 skips, and target-root separation; prove migration fidelity. |
| 4 | Test attestation, shared venv, and reviewer test evidence | high-assurance | Dispatch 3 merged and installed | Stop skipped, missing, substituted, and zero-assertion tests at the test gate; retain the shared-venv and sanitized-log design. |
| 5 | Verdict schema v4 and blocking-finding evaluation | high-assurance | Dispatch 4 merged, installed as parent, and on-box validation passed | Enforce complete criterion binding and mechanical blocker handling under the repaired parent test gate. |

Dispatch 1 must be reviewed and authorized as a trust-closure change even though it is behavior-preserving. Dispatch 2 is ordinary-risk only because its allowed paths exclude the dispatcher and all other gate components.

Dispatch 3 must be installed before Dispatch 4 begins so Dispatch 4 has parent-owned assertion-capable tests. Dispatch 4 must be installed as the active parent before Dispatch 5 begins. Merging code without the required installation and activation drill does not satisfy either dependency.

### 4.2 Per-spec allowed paths

The authorization artifacts must expand every allowed path to literal repository-relative paths. No generated spec may use a broad `scripts/**`, `tests/**`, or repository-wide allowance.

**Dispatch 1 — metrics extraction:**

- `scripts/dispatch.py`, limited to removing the metrics implementation, adding the lazy thin alias, and no other dispatcher behavior
- `scripts/metrics_report.py` (new)
- `tests/metrics_report.sh` (new)
- `tests/dispatch_gate4.sh`, limited to proving metrics alias compatibility and non-metrics import isolation

This dispatch is high-assurance because `scripts/dispatch.py` is in scope. Its approval artifact must bind the exact attempt and digest.

**Dispatch 2 — metrics semantics:**

- `scripts/metrics_report.py`
- `scripts/delegation_report.py`
- `tests/metrics_report.sh`
- `tests/delegation_report.sh`
- `tests/fixtures/metrics_semantics.json` (new)

`scripts/dispatch.py` and `scripts/dispatch` are explicitly excluded. The installed alias from Dispatch 1 obtains the corrected behavior by calling the standalone module.

**Dispatch 3 — assertion-event migration:**

- `scripts/test`
- `scripts/lib/test_attest.sh` (new)
- `tests/assertion_migration.sh` (new)
- Every other currently tracked `tests/*.sh` that must acquire assertion-event calls, exit-77 conversion, or target-root separation. Before authorization, the generated spec must replace this sentence with the literal output of `git ls-files 'tests/*.sh'`; no non-test path may be added through that expansion.

This dispatch may not change dispatcher gate logic, policy, venv setup, CI, verdict handling, or reviewer construction.

**Dispatch 4 — attestation, venv, and reviewer evidence:**

- `scripts/dispatch.py`, limited to required-test selection, trusted-source execution/result validation, test evidence persistence, isolated-unit construction, and reviewer prompt construction
- `scripts/test`
- `scripts/test_runner.py` (new)
- `scripts/test-policy.json` (new)
- `scripts/setup-worker-user.sh`
- `tests/dispatch_gate4.sh`
- `tests/dispatch_parallel.sh`
- `tests/worker_isolation.sh`
- `tests/test_attestation.sh` (new)
- `tests/reviewer_evidence.sh` (new)
- `tests/fixtures/verdict_integrity/spec015_skips.log` (new synthetic regression fixture)
- `.github/workflows/ci.yml`

Any changed or added test in this dispatch is supplemental during its own candidate attempt and must be named by exact old/new blob identity in the high-assurance approval artifact. It becomes authoritative only after merge, installation, and the activation drill.

**Dispatch 5 — verdict v4 and blockers:**

- `scripts/dispatch.py`, limited to review parsing, v4 binding validation, `evaluate_binary_review()`, and reviewer prompt/schema-version instructions
- `scripts/verdict.schema.json`
- `tests/dispatch_gate4.sh`
- `tests/verdict_integrity.sh` (new)
- `tests/fixtures/verdict_v4.json` (new)

Changes outside the corresponding set are scope failures, not occasions to enlarge the spec during implementation.

### 4.3 Parent-owned required-test policy

`scripts/test-policy.json` is a versioned, parent-owned mapping from changed path classes to exact required test IDs and execution lanes.

The policy must implement these decisions:

1. Classify both old and new paths of a rename from the approved base-to-candidate diff.
2. Changes to dispatcher, verdict schema, spec schema, test runner, test policy, requirements, CI, isolation setup, test helper, or a required test require the full trust suite supported by the current lane.
3. Changes under an unrecognized path in `scripts/`, `tests/`, `specs/`, `.github/workflows/`, or `.orchestrator/` require the full trust suite.
4. Ordinary product/helper paths map to their exact existing regression tests. A changed path with no mapping is a policy error, never “no required tests.”
5. On-box-only tests such as worker isolation are mandatory for a high-assurance dispatch that touches their boundary. CI records them as not runnable in that lane but cannot authorize deployment by itself.
6. Candidate changes to the policy do not affect that candidate’s gate. They become active only after merge, authorization, installation, and parent-version recording.
7. Required IDs resolve against the installed parent checkout and are bound to that commit’s blob identities. The candidate worktree is used only as the target under test.
8. Candidate changes to a required-test path trigger both the trusted parent execution and a separate supplemental candidate-test execution. No candidate result is admitted to the required-result namespace.
9. Candidate-added tests are never silently promoted into the required set. Promotion requires merge, parent installation, policy activation, and the post-install drill.

### 4.4 Trusted test source, candidate target, and legitimate test changes

The runner maintains two distinct roots:

- `trusted_test_root`: the installed parent checkout recorded in the attempt manifest.
- `candidate_target_root`: the candidate worktree at the bound `worker_commit`.

A required trust test’s executable, assertion helper, policy metadata, and trusted fixtures resolve from `trusted_test_root`. Code and data explicitly designated as the system under test resolve from `candidate_target_root`. The runner supplies both roots through a clean parent-constructed environment. Migrated tests must use the parent helper to resolve trusted support files and the target-root helper to resolve candidate paths. A required test that resolves its own script location as the system-under-test root, reads a helper from the candidate tree, or cannot demonstrate the root separation fails with `HARNESS_ERROR`.

Before launch, the runner obtains each required test’s expected Git blob identity from the recorded parent commit and verifies the opened regular file against it. It opens without following symlinks and executes the verified descriptor or an equivalently race-safe path. The attestation records the parent commit, blob identity, trusted source root, candidate commit, and candidate target root.

For a candidate-modified required-test path:

1. The trusted parent copy still executes against the candidate target and supplies the only required result.
2. The candidate copy executes once as a supplemental test in a separately labelled namespace.
3. Supplemental assertion events cannot use, overwrite, duplicate, or satisfy a trusted required ID.
4. A supplemental skip, failure, malformed event, or harness error blocks the attempt; a supplemental PASS adds evidence but does not weaken the trusted result.
5. The high-assurance approval artifact must enumerate each changed test path and its old and new blob identity. An unlisted test delta invalidates approval.
6. After merge and installation, the new parent copy is rerun against the exact merged commit before activation. Only then may its blob become authoritative for later candidates.

A legitimate change that alters test implementation without contradicting the old test may land normally if both trusted and supplemental copies pass.

A legitimate behavior change that contradicts an installed parent test must use a two-stage compatibility sequence:

1. Land an implementation and test update that remains compatible with the installed trusted test.
2. Merge and install that test as new parent content and pass the activation drill.
3. In a following high-assurance dispatch, remove the compatibility behavior while the updated parent test is authoritative.

If no compatibility bridge is technically possible, the normal pipeline fails closed. Proceeding would require a separately scoped operator bootstrap authorization that names the exact retired and replacement test blobs, explains why the old test cannot remain valid, and defines independent validation. This plan does not grant or create that exceptional authority.

### 4.5 Test-attestation protocol

The installed parent `scripts/test_runner.py` performs deterministic orchestration using only the Python standard library. `scripts/test` remains the public entry point.

For every required trusted test, the runner:

1. Resolves the exact repository-relative ID beneath the installed parent checkout without following symlinks.
2. Verifies the test file’s Git blob identity against the recorded parent commit.
3. Creates a per-run cryptographic nonce and a dedicated assertion-event channel.
4. Injects the test ID, nonce, trusted source root, and candidate target root as fixed parent-controlled values.
5. Launches the exact trusted test once using argv, never a generated shell command.
6. Counts JSON-line assertion events emitted through the installed parent’s `scripts/lib/test_attest.sh`.
7. Captures exit status and output independently of those events.
8. Runs any changed candidate copy separately under a supplemental namespace.
9. Writes the aggregate result itself to a parent-created attempt-local regular file using a temporary file, `fsync`, and atomic rename.

An assertion event contains exactly:

```json
{
  "version": 1,
  "run_nonce": "<nonce>",
  "test_id": "tests/example.sh",
  "sequence": 1,
  "event": "assertion",
  "ok": true,
  "name": "short stable assertion name"
}
```

A prerequisite failure emits a `skip` diagnostic event and exits `77`. It never emits a passing assertion. Test helpers must evaluate the guarded condition before emitting an event. Failed assertions emit `ok: false` and then cause a nonzero test exit. The helper API must not expose an unconditional “record pass” operation to migrated tests.

The aggregate attestation contains:

- `schema_version`
- `run_nonce`
- `parent_gate_commit`
- `trusted_test_root`
- `spec_digest`
- `base_sha`
- `worker_commit`
- `candidate_target_root`
- exact ordered `required_test_ids`
- `trusted_required_results`, with parent commit and blob hash per ID
- `candidate_supplemental_results`, separately namespaced
- one result per executed ID with `status`, `exit_code`, and `assertions_executed`
- overall status
- creation timestamp

Per-test statuses are `PASS`, `SKIP`, `FAIL`, or `HARNESS_ERROR`. The test gate has only authorization outcomes `pass` and `failed_test`; a required skip is diagnostic `SKIP` but authorizes nothing.

Supplemental immutable-spec `test_command` execution remains required and any nonzero result fails. It cannot satisfy the parent-required test set. If it calls `scripts/test`, it receives the same source-separated attestation behavior.

### 4.6 Verdict v4 criterion normalization and binding

Schema v4 requires each criterion entry to contain:

- `criterion_index`: one-based integer
- `criterion`: nonempty string
- `result`: `MET` or `UNMET`
- `evidence`: nonempty string

Dispatcher validation compares entry `i` only with spec acceptance criterion `i`; it does not perform unordered or fuzzy matching.

Normalization is exactly:

1. Apply Unicode NFKC.
2. Convert CRLF and CR to LF.
3. Strip leading and trailing Unicode whitespace from the entire string.
4. Replace every remaining maximal Unicode-whitespace run, including newlines, with one ASCII space.

Normalization does not case-fold, remove punctuation, render Markdown, resolve links, reorder clauses, or otherwise rewrite wording. If two spec criteria normalize to the same text, their positions remain distinct and both entries are required.

Validation order is:

1. Size and JSON parse.
2. Schema v4.
3. `spec_digest`, `base_sha`, and `worker_commit` binding.
4. Exact count.
5. Sequential indices.
6. Normalized positional text binding.
7. Binary review evaluation.

Failure at any stage records a non-PASS review outcome and prevents PR creation.

The v4 top-level object, every criterion object, and every finding object use `additionalProperties: false`. There is no extensible v4 authorization object left open to implementer discretion. Legacy display-only readers are separate from the v4 authorization schema and are not changed by this rule.

### 4.7 Structured findings and blocker predicate

Each of the existing finding domains becomes an array:

```json
{
  "scope_findings": [],
  "regression_findings": [
    {
      "severity": "advisory",
      "summary": "Non-blocking observation",
      "evidence": "Bound evidence"
    }
  ],
  "security_findings": [
    {
      "severity": "blocker",
      "summary": "Trust boundary bypass",
      "evidence": "Bound evidence"
    }
  ]
}
```

The blocker predicate is:

```text
blocking =
    findings is not an array
    OR any entry is not an object
    OR any required field is absent or invalid
    OR any undeclared field is present
    OR severity is not exactly "advisory" or "blocker"
    OR any severity is exactly "blocker"
```

An empty array is the only representation of “no findings.” There is no `none`, `clear`, `low`, `medium`, `high`, or `critical` severity. This prevents ambiguous threshold mapping. `evaluate_binary_review()` defensively rechecks the predicate even after schema validation.

A review passes only when:

- the bound top-level verdict is PASS;
- v4 schema and all bindings succeeded;
- every required criterion is present and `MET`;
- all three finding arrays are structurally valid; and
- none contains a blocker.

### 4.8 Shared gate virtual environment

The trusted environment is `/srv/codexwork/venvs/gate/<sha256>`, where the digest is over the installed parent checkout’s `scripts/requirements.txt`.

`scripts/setup-worker-user.sh` must:

1. Build in a sibling temporary directory with restrictive umask.
2. Install exactly the trusted requirements file.
3. Verify imports and pinned direct-package versions.
4. Record digest, Python implementation/version, and verification result in a root-owned marker.
5. Remove group/other write permission recursively.
6. Grant only the traversal/read/execute access required by `codex-worker`.
7. Atomically rename the verified environment into place.
8. Remain idempotent when the verified digest already exists.
9. Retain older digest directories for rollback.

Before tests, the parent dispatcher verifies the marker, ownership, mode, digest, and imports under the same isolated `codex-worker` boundary. It sets a fixed PATH beginning with the selected venv, plus `PYTHONNOUSERSITE=1`, `PYTHONDONTWRITEBYTECODE=1`, `PIP_NO_INDEX=1`, and `PIP_DISABLE_PIP_VERSION_CHECK=1`.

### 4.9 Sanitized reviewer evidence

The parent opens only the expected attempt-local regular `test.log` without following symlinks. It hashes the complete file, then retains at most the final 16 KiB and final 80 logical lines.

Sanitization must:

- decode invalid UTF-8 with replacement;
- normalize line endings;
- remove ANSI/ECMA-48 sequences;
- replace NUL and remaining C0/C1 controls;
- serialize retained lines as ASCII-escaped JSON;
- escape literal `<`, `>`, and `&`;
- record full hash, byte counts, line counts, and truncation;
- detect replacement or mutation during reading.

The prompt places the trusted attestation before the log, labels the log as untrusted evidence, and encloses it in a fixed control-plane delimiter. Fixed review instructions follow the evidence block. Prompt input is provided through stdin or a trusted prompt file, never shell interpolation.

### 4.10 Metrics extraction and definitions

Dispatch 1 extracts the current metrics implementation into `scripts/metrics_report.py` without changing calculations, labels, default selection, ordering, text formatting, JSON fields, exit behavior, or error semantics. `scripts/dispatch.py` retains only a lazy thin alias for the metrics subcommand. The reporting module is not imported during dispatcher startup or any non-metrics command, and no gate code depends on it.

Dispatch 2 changes only the standalone reporting surfaces. `delegation_report.py` may state only whether a mainline commit was matched to retained orchestrator evidence. The complement bucket is named `not_attributed_to_orchestrator`; it must not imply an actor.

The metrics implementation first groups attempt records by spec ID, orders valid attempts numerically, and classifies each spec once:

- **Straight-through:** attempt 1 reached normal `merged`, no replacement/retry/later attempt exists, and retained result evidence shows all normal gates passed.
- **Completed but not straight-through:** terminal failure, replacement/retry, or eventual later-attempt merge.
- **In progress:** no terminal result; excluded from the rate.
- **Malformed/incomplete:** cannot be classified safely; excluded and reported as a diagnostic count.

The output exposes numerator, denominator, excluded counts, and either a numeric rate or `null`. Human-readable output derives from the same structured calculation.

### 4.11 Alternatives considered

1. **Parse `SKIP` from `test.log`.** Rejected because logs are worker-controlled, forgeable, and ambiguous.

2. **Treat exit zero as proof and improve only the reviewer prompt.** Rejected because SPEC-015 would still pass the test gate; reviewer quality cannot repair false control-plane evidence.

3. **Treat every platform skip as a global failure.** Rejected because requiredness depends on changed paths and execution lane. Optional tests may remain recorded as skipped, but a required skip always fails.

4. **Let candidate policy, candidate dispatcher, or candidate test content certify itself.** Rejected because it violates the bootstrap invariant and permits self-exemption or vacuous passing stubs.

5. **Fail every legitimate test-file change permanently.** Rejected because tests must evolve. Parent execution plus supplemental candidate execution, post-install promotion, and the compatibility sequence permit evolution without self-certification.

6. **Accept a candidate replacement test after ordinary reviewer approval.** Rejected because SPEC-015 demonstrates that reviewer prose cannot substitute for mechanically truthful test provenance.

7. **Use schema `minItems` or ask the reviewer to count criteria.** Rejected because a static shared schema does not bind the list to the selected spec. A per-attempt generated schema could encode the count, but dispatcher-side positional validation is simpler to audit and also binds normalized text and indices.

8. **Match criteria as an unordered set or use fuzzy similarity.** Rejected because duplicates and near-matches become ambiguous. Positional normalized equality is deterministic and reviewable.

9. **Search blocker prose for words such as “critical” or “RCE.”** Rejected because substring policies are language-dependent and both miss and invent blockers.

10. **Use several severity levels and choose a threshold.** Rejected for Phase 1 because it creates unnecessary policy decisions. `advisory` versus `blocker` directly models the binary gate.

11. **Expose the operator venv or install per worktree.** Rejected because both weaken isolation and reproducibility.

12. **Provide the complete raw log to the reviewer.** Rejected because it is unbounded and structurally unsafe. The raw artifact remains retained; the prompt receives a bounded representation.

13. **Attribute unmatched merges through Git author/committer identity.** Rejected because author, committer, merger, and automation identity are not equivalent and do not establish the route by which the change entered the branch.

14. **Compute straight-through rate per attempt.** Rejected because retries inflate the population and allow one spec to contribute multiple times.

15. **Let an ordinary-risk metrics worker modify `scripts/dispatch.py` with a function-level scope promise.** Rejected because the scope gate enforces paths, not function boundaries. Extraction is therefore a separate high-assurance predecessor.

16. **Reclassify all metrics semantics as high-assurance without extraction.** Rejected because it leaves a read-only reporting concern unnecessarily coupled to the gate and gives Phase 2 no standalone reporting surface.

17. **Migrate all shell tests in the same dispatch as runner, policy, venv, CI, and reviewer changes.** Rejected because the heterogeneous trust-critical diff would dilute review attention. The homogeneous migration and its mutation proof are separated.

18. **Ship all changes in one high-assurance spec.** Rejected because metrics extraction, metrics semantics, mechanical test migration, repaired attestation, and verdict v4 have distinct risk and activation boundaries.

## 5. Affected boundaries & consumers

| Boundary or consumer | Effect |
|---|---|
| Installed parent dispatcher | Becomes the sole authority for required-test selection, trusted-content execution, attestation validation, test-to-review transition, v4 validation, and blocker evaluation. |
| Installed parent test suite | Supplies authoritative required-test executables, helpers, fixtures, policy bindings, and blob identities. |
| Candidate worktree | Supplies code and data targets plus supplemental test copies only; cannot choose or replace its gate implementation or required trust tests. |
| `scripts/test` users | Receive explicit PASS/SKIP/FAIL summaries and machine attestation rather than exit-code-only aggregation. |
| Existing `tests/*.sh` | Acquire assertion events, exit-77 prerequisite skips, trusted-source/candidate-target separation, and mutation-fidelity validation in a separate dispatch. |
| Candidate test changes | Run additionally, require exact high-assurance approval binding, and become authoritative only after merge, installation, and activation replay. |
| `codex-worker` isolation | Gains read/execute access to one trusted digest venv, never write access or operator-home access. |
| `scripts/verdict.schema.json` | Becomes v4 and rejects legacy/prose-only review output for authorization. |
| Reviewer prompt | Gains trusted attestation and sanitized log evidence; requires structured findings and complete criteria. |
| `evaluate_binary_review()` callers | Malformed findings now fail closed even if schema validation was skipped. |
| Attempt manifests/results | Gain parent-gate identity, trusted-test source bindings, and structured test-attestation references. Historical formats remain display-only. |
| CI job `ci` | Must create a CI-local pinned venv, exercise portable attestation tests, and retain its exact job name and non-matrix form. |
| Setup/operator procedure | Must provision and verify the shared digest venv before activating Dispatch 4. |
| `scripts/metrics_report.py` | Becomes the standalone, read-only metrics implementation and the only ordinary-risk metrics code surface. |
| Dispatcher metrics alias | Remains a lazy compatibility entry point; non-metrics commands do not import the reporting module. |
| Delegation-report consumers | See neutral attribution naming; consumers of renamed JSON properties must update atomically. |
| Dispatch-metrics consumers | Receive spec-level numerator/denominator and nullable rate semantics. |
| Phase 2 measurement work | Remains blocked until Dispatch 2 is merged and validated. |
| Historical SPEC-015 evidence | Read-only regression input; never migrated or rewritten. |
| PR creation | Remains unreachable after failed trusted test attestation, malformed v4, incomplete criteria, or blocker findings. |

Transitive dependency closure includes the dispatcher CLI wrapper, isolated systemd unit construction, attempt result serialization, review-request archive, review-result readers, reporting fixtures, CI, setup verification, parent test installation, target-root adapters, activation drills, and any code that assumes finding fields are strings or that a successful aggregate test exit implies executed trusted tests.

## 6. Ordered implementation steps

1. **Freeze and verify the baseline.** Record the base commit, installed parent executable/commit, requirements digest, current test inventory, current metrics output, metrics alias behavior, and hashes of all SPEC-015/1 evidence. Expand Dispatch 3’s `tests/*.sh` allowance to literal paths before authorization.

2. **Add extraction parity regressions for Dispatch 1.** Capture current metrics text, JSON, exit, selection, and error behavior. Add a non-metrics command probe that detects whether the metrics module is imported.

3. **Extract the metrics implementation.** Move the implementation into `scripts/metrics_report.py`; retain only a lazy thin alias in `scripts/dispatch.py`. Do not change metrics semantics.

4. **Validate and activate Dispatch 1.** Prove parity, prove non-metrics import isolation, run focused tests and `./scripts/test`, complete high-assurance challenge and operator approval, merge to `integration`, and install the extracted parent before ordinary metrics work begins.

5. **Implement Dispatch 2 regression fixtures.** Add `tests/fixtures/metrics_semantics.json` with the exact five-spec population defined in R6. First assert the current rate/attribution behavior fails the new expectations.

6. **Correct attribution naming.** In `scripts/delegation_report.py` and `scripts/metrics_report.py`, rename actor-attributing text and machine fields to `not_attributed_to_orchestrator`; add the actor-unknown explanation and remove compatibility aliases that preserve the false claim.

7. **Correct straight-through calculation.** In `scripts/metrics_report.py`, group by spec, classify each spec once, expose numerator/denominator/exclusions, return `null` for zero denominator, and make text output consume the structured result.

8. **Validate and land Dispatch 2.** Run focused tests and full `./scripts/test`, confirm no trust-closure path changed, dispatch through the installed parent, merge to `integration`, and record that Phase 2’s prerequisite is satisfied.

9. **Add migration-fidelity regressions for Dispatch 3.** Define every assertion-helper form and shell assertion idiom. Add mutation cases that force guarded conditions false and require `ok: false` plus nonzero exit.

10. **Add assertion-event support.** Create `scripts/lib/test_attest.sh`; make helpers evaluate conditions before emitting results and omit any unconditional pass-recording API.

11. **Migrate the tracked shell suite.** Convert assertions and genuine prerequisite skips to assertion events and exit `77`. Add trusted-source/candidate-target root resolution without changing the substantive conditions being tested.

12. **Update the public test wrapper for migration compatibility.** Make `scripts/test` report child exit `77` as `SKIP` while preserving the pre-attestation aggregate behavior needed during the migration predecessor.

13. **Validate and install Dispatch 3.** Run the full suite, the mutation drill, target-root separation probes, challenge, and operator-approved high-assurance dispatch. Merge and install it so its test content and helper become the parent source for Dispatch 4.

14. **Add failing attestation regressions for Dispatch 4.** Cover required skip, zero assertions, missing/duplicate ID, stale nonce, malformed event, inconsistent exit/result, source-blob mismatch, target-root mismatch, policy gaps, candidate-gate marker, candidate required-test stub substitution, reviewer non-invocation, SPEC-015 replay, and adversarial logs.

15. **Introduce the parent runner and policy.** Create `scripts/test_runner.py` and `scripts/test-policy.json`; retain `scripts/test` as the stable entry point. Implement trusted blob resolution, source/target separation, exact ID execution, supplemental candidate-test execution, event validation, nonce/binding checks, atomic aggregate output, and fail-closed status derivation.

16. **Wire attestation into the test gate.** Update `scripts/dispatch.py` to classify actual changed paths, invoke the installed parent runner and tests, validate the aggregate, persist it, and make literal trusted-attestation PASS a precondition for reviewer invocation.

17. **Provision the shared venv.** Extend `scripts/setup-worker-user.sh` with content-addressed atomic provisioning, import/version verification, ownership/mode checks, and idempotence.

18. **Wire the venv into isolation.** Resolve the trusted parent requirements digest, run the worker-boundary import probe, set the fixed environment, expose the venv read-only, and add negative tests for every forbidden fallback.

19. **Add reviewer evidence.** Implement the safe log snapshot/sanitizer and include both trusted attestation and sanitized log tail in the prompt. Preserve the full raw log and hash.

20. **Update CI.** Keep the job named exactly `ci`, do not add a matrix, create a CI-local venv from `scripts/requirements.txt`, and run portable attestation, source-substitution, and negative-skip tests. On-box isolation remains an additional activation requirement.

21. **Replay SPEC-015.** Read the actual recorded log and attempt metadata without writes. Require `legacy_missing_attestation`, no reviewer call, no PR call, and identical before/after hashes.

22. **Authorize, merge, install, and activate Dispatch 4.** Complete high-assurance challenge and dual validation. Verify exact test-delta approval bindings, provision the shared venv, install the merged dispatcher and tests as parent, rerun newly authoritative tests against the exact merged commit, record the parent commit, and pass the on-box isolation drill before starting Dispatch 5.

23. **Add failing verdict-v4 regressions for Dispatch 5.** Cover count mismatch, missing/extra/reordered/duplicate criteria, normalization boundaries, all blocker domains, unknown severities, undeclared properties, malformed evaluator inputs, and legacy display-only behavior.

24. **Implement schema v4.** Update `scripts/verdict.schema.json` with strict top-level versioning, structured criteria, structured finding arrays, required fields, enums, bounds, and `additionalProperties: false` on the v4 top-level object, criterion objects, and finding objects.

25. **Implement dispatcher binding.** Add deterministic normalization, positional count/text/index validation, and explicit failure reasons before calling binary evaluation.

26. **Harden binary evaluation.** Update `evaluate_binary_review()` with the precise blocker predicate and defensive fail-closed behavior. Update the reviewer prompt to request only v4.

27. **Validate and land Dispatch 5.** Run focused and full tests through the newly installed Dispatch 4 parent, complete high-assurance challenge and detached SOL design review, resolve all blockers, and merge only after operator authorization.

## 7. Failure modes & blast radius

| Trigger | Consequence | Mitigation |
|---|---|---|
| Required test skips but exits zero | False test PASS could recur | Assertion count and structured status override aggregate exit; review is never called. |
| Test exits zero without assertions | Empty test body is certified | Zero assertions is an explicit failed-test reason. |
| Candidate removes or renames a required test | Coverage silently disappears | Parent policy and trusted parent IDs still execute; the candidate delta is separately recorded and approved. |
| Candidate rewrites a required test as a passing stub | Candidate-controlled assertions falsely certify coverage | Candidate test results are supplemental only; the verified parent blob supplies the required result. |
| Candidate-added test is treated as authoritative in its own attempt | New gate behavior self-certifies | New tests remain supplemental until merge, installation, and post-install replay from the new parent. |
| Legitimate new behavior contradicts an installed parent test | Safe change cannot pass the old invariant | Use the two-stage compatibility sequence; if impossible, fail closed pending separately scoped bootstrap authority not granted here. |
| Trusted test accidentally targets the parent checkout | Candidate is not actually tested | Explicit source/target roots, target-commit binding, adapter validation, and target-root mismatch failure. |
| Migrated assertion emits PASS before evaluating its condition | Green suite gives vacuous evidence | Helper API ordering plus mutation drills requiring `ok: false` and nonzero exit for induced failures. |
| Candidate edits its policy to exempt itself | Self-certification | Active policy comes from installed parent, not candidate. |
| Candidate gate implementation is invoked | Bootstrap trust collapses | Absolute parent path/commit binding plus marker regression test. |
| Assertion JSON is malformed or replayed | Incorrect attestation | Nonce, sequence, ID, source blob, target commit, base/head, and parent-commit validation; malformed input fails. |
| Shared venv is missing or writable | Tests skip or worker contaminates later gates | Preflight ownership/mode/import checks and no fallback. |
| Requirements change in candidate | Candidate influences gate dependencies | Use parent digest and block pending post-merge provisioning. |
| Reviewer log contains injection text | Reviewer instructions may be displaced | Bounded JSON escaping, fixed delimiters, explicit untrusted-data warning, fixed instructions after evidence. |
| Log changes while read | Reviewer sees evidence not matching retained hash | Stable-file checks; block review. |
| v4 criterion normalization is too permissive | Wrong criterion binds | NFKC plus whitespace only; no case or punctuation folding. |
| v4 criterion normalization is too strict | Harmless formatting rejects verdict | Defined whitespace normalization handles line wrapping; rejection is safe and reviewer may be rerun. |
| Reviewer omits a criterion | Partial PASS | Exact count and positional binding reject it. |
| Reviewer reports a blocker with PASS | Dangerous change advances | Structured blocker predicate forces failure. |
| Reviewer uses an unknown severity | Threshold ambiguity | Unknown is malformed and fail-closed. |
| Evaluator is called without schema validation | Malformed data bypasses controls | Evaluator independently validates finding container, fields, and severity shape. |
| Legacy verdict is supplied to a resumed attempt | Old weak schema authorizes work | Display-only compatibility; authorization requires v4. |
| Ordinary metrics worker can modify dispatcher gate code | Reporting change crosses risk boundary | Behavior-preserving high-assurance extraction precedes semantics; ordinary allowed paths exclude dispatcher files. |
| Metrics module is imported by gate commands | Reporting failure affects authorization availability or behavior | Lazy metrics-only alias and regression proving non-metrics commands do not import the module. |
| Extraction changes metrics behavior before semantic fixtures | Baseline and semantic correction become conflated | Field-for-field parity fixture and separate high-assurance extraction dispatch. |
| Metrics groups attempts incorrectly | Phase 2 learns from distorted rates | Fixed five-spec fixture with invariant expected counts. |
| Neutral merge label breaks a consumer | Reporting job fails | Update all in-repo consumers in Dispatch 2; no misleading alias. Roll back that independent spec if necessary. |
| Zero eligible metrics denominator | Divide-by-zero or deceptive 0% | Return `null`/`N/A` with explicit denominator zero. |
| Migration and gate redesign are reviewed as one heterogeneous diff | Trust-critical mistakes receive diluted review | Separate homogeneous migration from runner, policy, isolation, CI, and prompt changes. |
| New gate is over-strict | Dispatch availability decreases | Fail closed, preserve evidence, repair under a new high-assurance spec; never restore exit-code-only authorization. |
| New gate is under-strict | False PASS and unsafe PR | Worst case is an incorrectly authorized trust-boundary change. Immediately stop dispatch, preserve artifacts, revoke affected authorization, and roll forward the gate before resuming. |

The only irreversible outputs are retained attempt evidence, review artifacts, and any already-opened PR. None may be rewritten. No production deployment or merge to `main` is authorized by this plan.

## 8. Validation plan

### 8.1 Regression proofs that must fail before implementation

1. Run the SPEC-015 replay adapter against its exit-zero log without structured attestation. Current behavior can advance; the new assertion requires a blocking result.
2. Replace a candidate copy of a selected required test with a well-formed passing stub. Candidate-source execution would accept it; the repaired design must still execute and bind the trusted parent blob.
3. Induce a guarded-condition failure after a naïve assertion migration. A miswired migration may remain green; the repaired helper and mutation drill must emit `ok: false` and fail.
4. Validate a PASS containing one `MET` criterion against a multi-criterion spec. Current schema/evaluator accepts the supplied subset; v4 must reject it.
5. Evaluate an all-`MET` PASS whose security finding is a blocker. Current evaluator does not use the content; the new evaluator must reject it.
6. Run the five-spec metrics fixture through current reporting. At least the attribution label or numerator/denominator must disagree with R6.

### 8.2 Dispatch 1 validation

- Capture and compare metrics text output, structured output, ordering, defaults, error output, and exit status before and after extraction.
- Invoke metrics through both the dispatcher alias and standalone reporting module and prove semantic identity.
- Prove representative non-metrics dispatcher commands do not import `scripts/metrics_report.py`.
- Make the reporting module unavailable in a probe and prove non-metrics gate behavior is unaffected.
- Run focused tests and `./scripts/test`.
- Inspect the diff to confirm no dispatcher behavior beyond removal of metrics implementation and creation of the lazy alias changed.
- Require the operator’s per-attempt high-assurance approval artifact.

### 8.3 Dispatch 2 validation

- `tests/delegation_report.sh` proves neutral naming in text and machine output.
- `tests/metrics_report.sh` proves the dispatcher alias obtains its implementation from the standalone module without a Dispatch 2 change to `scripts/dispatch.py`.
- The metrics fixture proves numerator `1`, denominator `3`, rate `1/3`, one in-progress exclusion, and one malformed exclusion.
- A retry-count mutation proves spec-level invariance.
- Empty input proves `null`/`N/A`.
- `./scripts/test` passes.
- The diff contains no dispatcher, gate-transition, authorization, attempt-result, or test-policy path.

### 8.4 Dispatch 3 validation

- `tests/assertion_migration.sh` exercises every assertion-helper form with both a passing and induced-failing condition.
- Every induced failure emits `ok: false` before exit and produces a nonzero exit.
- A representative migrated test for each distinct shell assertion idiom is mutation-tested by forcing the guarded condition false.
- Static inspection confirms no migrated test invokes an unconditional pass-recording primitive.
- Genuine prerequisite absence produces exit `77` and no passing assertion.
- `scripts/test` distinguishes PASS, SKIP, and FAIL while preserving the predecessor’s aggregate compatibility behavior until Dispatch 4 activates.
- Source/target probes prove migrated tests obtain helpers and fixtures from the trusted root while resolving the system under test from the candidate target root.
- The substantive pre-migration and post-migration conditions are mapped in the review artifact; unexplained assertion removal, weakening, or replacement is a blocker.
- Run `./scripts/test`, high-assurance challenge, and operator-approved dispatch before installing the migrated suite as parent content.

### 8.5 Dispatch 4 validation

- `tests/test_attestation.sh` exercises every R1 malformed/negative case and a fully passing multi-test case.
- A required trusted test printing `SKIP` and exiting zero fails at the test gate.
- A required trusted zero-assertion test fails before review.
- A candidate dispatcher marker proves the candidate gate is not invoked.
- A candidate required-test stub that emits correctly formed passing events cannot satisfy or replace the trusted parent result.
- Source-commit, blob-hash, and candidate-target mismatches fail before review.
- Candidate-modified test results are persisted only under `candidate_supplemental_results`.
- `tests/dispatch_gate4.sh` and `tests/dispatch_parallel.sh` execute real trusted assertions against the candidate target with the shared venv rather than skipping.
- `tests/worker_isolation.sh` proves shared-venv read/execute, write denial, home denial, and network denial.
- The real on-box SPEC-015 replay blocks and leaves all historical hashes unchanged.
- The synthetic CI fixture reproduces the same missing-attestation failure.
- Adversarial logs prove the 16 KiB/80-line cap, escaping, control removal, stable hash metadata, delimiter safety, and absence from argv.
- Missing, symlinked, replaced, or raced logs block reviewer invocation.
- `.github/workflows/ci.yml` installs pinned requirements and passes portable tests while retaining job name `ci`.
- `./scripts/test` passes in the provisioned development environment.
- Every test delta in the candidate is bound by exact old/new blob identity in the operator approval artifact.
- After merge, the newly installed parent reruns all newly authoritative tests against the exact merged commit before activation.
- The exact isolated on-box activation drill passes before the new parent is enabled.

### 8.6 Dispatch 5 validation

A table-driven `tests/verdict_integrity.sh` must include:

- N correct criteria: PASS.
- N−1, N+1, duplicate, reordered, wrong-index, invented-text cases: reject.
- Exact and whitespace/NFKC-normalized text: bind.
- Case, punctuation, Markdown, or wording changes: reject.
- Undeclared top-level, criterion, or finding properties: reject.
- All criteria `MET` plus scope blocker: reject.
- All criteria `MET` plus regression blocker: reject.
- All criteria `MET` plus security blocker: reject.
- Empty arrays and advisory-only arrays: eligible to pass.
- Missing, null, string, unknown-severity, or malformed findings: reject.
- Direct calls to `evaluate_binary_review()` without schema preprocessing: malformed inputs reject.
- Wrong spec digest, base SHA, or worker commit: reject.
- v1-v3: displayable but not authorizing.
- Review rejection always yields zero PR-opening calls.

Finally, run `./scripts/test` and the declared per-spec test command through the installed Dispatch 4 parent. High-assurance completion requires both Claude challenge and detached SOL design-review PASS, with all findings resolved and tests rerun after the final change.

## 9. Rollback / irreversibility

1. Roll back in reverse dependency order. Dispatch 5 may be reverted only while dispatch is paused; Dispatch 4 must remain active until no v4-dependent attempt is running.

2. Prefer roll-forward for gate defects. Restoring exit-code-only testing, candidate-content certification, incomplete criterion acceptance, or prose-only blocker handling is not an acceptable availability workaround.

3. If Dispatch 5 must be reverted, preserve every v4 artifact and add or retain display-only readers. Do not reinterpret v4 artifacts through the v3 authorization path.

4. If Dispatch 4 must be reverted, stop all new dispatches first, let active isolated units terminate, and revert dispatcher, runner, policy, CI, setup, and prompt changes as one internally consistent unit. Keep the independently installed assertion migration unless it is itself defective. Do not convert new failed-test outcomes to legacy passes.

5. If Dispatch 3 must be reverted, pause dispatch, restore `scripts/test`, the helper, and all migrated tests as one unit, and rerun substantive pre-migration tests. Do not leave a mixed suite in which some tests emit attestations and others silently rely on exit zero.

6. Digest-addressed venvs may remain in place; they are inert if unreferenced and support forward recovery. Remove one only after proving no active unit references it.

7. Dispatch 2 is independently reversible if a reporting consumer breaks. Its fixture and corrected definitions must remain the target semantics for the replacement; rollback does not unblock Phase 2.

8. Dispatch 1 may be reverted only through a high-assurance dispatcher change. If reverted, Dispatch 2’s standalone semantics must not be copied back into an ordinary-risk `scripts/dispatch.py` change.

9. Existing attempts, including SPEC-015, are irreversible evidence. Never edit or delete them during rollback.

10. After any rollback, rerun the applicable pre-change suite, integrity hashes, worker-isolation drill, trusted-test source/target drill, and parent-gate marker test before dispatch resumes.

## 10. Open questions / operator decisions

None. The operator’s existing per-dispatch approval, merge, installation, shared-venv provisioning, and activation duties remain required operational steps, not unresolved design decisions. An incompatible bootstrap outside the §4.4 compatibility sequence is explicitly not authorized by this plan and would require a new operator decision and artifact.

## 11. Provenance (filled during challenge/authorization — NOT by the drafter)

- **Challenge (Claude):** REVISE, with objections O1-O5 dated 2026-07-14. O1, O2, and O5 were blocking.
- **Disposition (drafter):** Revision 2 applies all five objections as recorded below.
- **Dual-validation (high-assurance/control-plane):** Fresh-context SOL adversarial critique of this same revision: pending. Claude verdict on this revision: pending. Unresolved disagreement escalates to operator.
- **Authorization:** Pending authorized-revision digest, authorizer, and date. Every high-assurance dispatch requires its per-attempt approval artifact. Any silent post-authorization edit voids authorization.
- **Completion reconciliation:** Pending; record followed / authorized-deviation / unauthorized-deviation after all five dispatches.

## Disposition record (revision 2)

- **O1 — revise.** Corrected the sole frontmatter identity and body title to `PLAN-003`, removed the duplicated pseudo-frontmatter, and retained applicable metadata in the real YAML frontmatter. Sections changed: YAML frontmatter; document title; §11.

- **O2 — accept-and-amend.** Adopted trusted parent/base content execution rather than allowing candidate copies to satisfy required tests. Required tests now resolve to verified blobs from the installed parent commit and target the candidate through a distinct target-root interface. Candidate-modified copies run only as separately namespaced supplemental tests. Legitimate test changes use post-install promotion; changes contradicting the old test use a two-stage compatibility sequence, while impossible compatibility cases fail closed pending separately scoped bootstrap authority not granted here. Added source/blob/target bindings, stub-substitution acceptance criteria, candidate-added-test handling, failure modes, approval bindings, and activation validation. Sections changed: §1; §2.2; R1; R5; R7; §§4.2-4.5; §5; implementation steps 14-22 in §6; §7; §§8.1 and 8.5; §9; §10.

- **O3 — accept-and-amend.** Added a required migration-fidelity mutation drill covering every assertion-helper form and a representative migrated test for each distinct shell assertion idiom. An induced guarded-condition failure must emit `ok: false` and exit nonzero, and the helper exposes no unconditional pass-recording API. Sections changed: §2.2 assumption 4; R1 acceptance criterion 10; §§4.5 and 4.11; Dispatch 3 paths in §4.2; implementation steps 9-13 in §6; §7; §§8.1 and 8.4.

- **O4 — accept-and-amend.** Split the homogeneous assertion-event, exit-77, and target-root migration into its own high-assurance predecessor. Runner, policy, dispatcher gate logic, venv, CI, and reviewer-evidence work remain in a following high-assurance dispatch. The verdict-v4 work is now the fifth dispatch and runs under the installed repaired parent. Sections changed: §1; §§4.1-4.2; §5; §6; §7; §§8.4-8.6; §9; §11.

- **O5 — accept-and-amend.** Adopted preferred option (a) with a necessary two-dispatch boundary: a high-assurance behavior-preserving extraction first moves metrics into `scripts/metrics_report.py` and leaves a lazy thin alias in `scripts/dispatch.py`; the following ordinary-risk semantic correction excludes both dispatcher files from its allowed paths. Added parity, lazy-import isolation, trust-closure acceptance criteria, failure modes, and rollback rules. Sections changed: §1; §2.1 fact 13; R6; §§4.1-4.2; §4.10; §4.11 alternatives 15-16; §5; implementation steps 2-8 in §6; §7; §§8.2-8.3; §9; §11.
